Philippines Stocks: Filinvest, MRC Allied, Petron, San Miguel

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-07-06T04:26:42Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-06/alliance-mrc-allied-pldt-rfm-philippines-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in Manila.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index decreased 0.9 percent
to 4,398.75, after climbing to a record yesterday.  Filinvest Land Inc. (FLI)  , a builder of homes, sank 1.6
percent to 1.25 pesos, snapping a four-day, 9.5 percent rally
that drove the shares yesterday to the highest since May 9.
“Some prudent investors are cashing in their gains,” said
Astro del Castillo, managing director at First Grade Holdings
Inc.  MRC Allied Inc. (MRC)  , a property developer, climbed 6
percent to 44.5 centavos, completing a three-day, 13 percent
rally. The company said it signed an agreement with Capital Gold
Pty Ltd. to explore and develop a copper-gold prospect in the
southern province of Surigao del Sur. Sydney-based Capital Gold
will give 40 million of its own shares to MRC Allied for a 40
percent stake in MRC Surigao, which will own the property, MRC
Allied said.  Petron Corp. (PCOR)  , the nation’s biggest oil refiner,
advanced 7.9 percent to 16.12 pesos, the highest close since
Jan. 14. The stock’s 12-month share price estimate was increased
to 17.48 pesos from 6.85 pesos by Erwin Balita, an analyst at SB
Equities Inc.. The brokerage kept a “buy” rating on the
shares.  San Miguel Corp. (SMC)  , which owns Petron, climbed
2.4 percent to 125.90 pesos, its highest level since April 12.  “Petron’s earnings are coming out better than expected,”
Balita said in a phone interview. “Its petrochemical products
have started to contribute and its impact on the bottom line
will be more pronounced next year.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
